description: As CRUAS DET SNCOIC I was responsible for the testing and fielding of the Lockheed Martin/Kaman KMAX. Conducted Mission Planning and Execution of Cargo Resupply Missions while supporting a Military User Assessment integrating CRUAS into MAGTF operations. Ensure the successful employment of the CRUAS and development of TTP's and SOP's to integrate the system into the MAGTF by attending all Conferences and Training required to support the program. Attended training conference with Lockheed Martin as a UAS SME to assist in the development, curriculum and standardization of training for CRUAS to match Marine Corps and Navy doctrine. Conducted eight simulator and 10 training sorties to qualify as a CRUAS Operator becoming the first Marine to operate and deliver cargo via UAS. Trained as an Unmanned Aircraft Commander (UAC) at Yuma Proving Grounds with the Lockheed Martin Deployment Team, assisting in the flight planning and preparation during the Lockheed Martin CRUAS Quick Reaction assessments aiding in the delivery of over 30,000 pounds of cargo during a five day period. Conducted site survey and set up of FOB Payne and FOB Geronimo during OEF to facilitate the combat operational test and evaluation for the KMAX. Assisted in the coordination, planning and execution of the first delivery of supplies by an unmanned aerial vehicle in a combat zone. Flew Lockheed Martin/ Kaman KMAX 12.4 hours first pilot time, 17.9 hours co-pilot time, 10.5 hours special crew time, and flew 39 mishap free sorties, delivering over 120,000 lbs of cargo to include generators, LAV motors, medical supplies, MRE's and water which were critical to the success of combat missions during OEF 11.2 and 12.1. Drafted the initial Standard Operating Procedures for CRUAS Helicopter Support Team operations which greatly expanded capabilities beyond the original Concept of Operations and allowing the retrograde of equipment of supplies.

description: Harris acquired the CHI Systems San Diego business unit on Feb 1, 2010. Harris discontinued Engineering in the San Diego office on March 15th, 2013. While at Harris: I worked on a team integrating the MUOS waveform into the 117G radio on the initial parts of this effort. Led the effort to modify the DSP platform and some specific waveform code to allow all the Narrow Band Waveforms (VULOS, SINCGARS, P25, DAMA, IW, HPW, and SCM) to operate in the UHF L-Band Amplifier. Ported the Talon waveform from the Falcon II architecture to the Falcon III architecture in order to run the waveform on a 7800 international MP. Was responsible for some Red side GPP portions as well as major portions of the Black GPP/DSP design, implementation and testing while working with a remote team. Ported the P25 Trunking waveform from the Harris Unity radio to the 310M international hand held to provide a proof of concept of having Trunking on a military radio. Assumed a technical role writing mostly DSP software as well as a management role to integrate a team in San Diego and Rochester along with support from our Lynchburg Virginia office with some of the best engineers in all three offices. I was able to demonstrate this technology at LA AFB, Tinker AFB in Oklahoma, Seattle Bangor Military Base, and Langley AFB to support potential sales efforts. Worked on a special Harris project called GR-100 to create a product using MEMS IMU technology targeting first responders and eventually military to provide near real-time Situational Awareness and tracking of dismounted units. After the acquisition of CHI Systems in San Diego, I continued the lead effort to create a product out of C3CORE/DC4S into a Harris C4ISR product which is now called Falcon Command.

description: Lead engineer for LSS' Land C3I Business Unit since its creation in 2008. LLS' goal was to provide C4ISR products. Led the software productizing effort for transitioning DC4S into an off the shelf product. Was lead engineer for an IMU navigation and software development effort in support of Raytheon's Ground Soldier System (GSS) program. Was the program manager and chief software engineer for the Decision Support Toolbox (DSTB) insertion into Northrop Grumman's Joint Common Tactical Workstation, and for translation of the Terrain Analysis Kit (TAK) software into Arabic for Lockheed Martin as well as the MAGTF Intelligence Collection Application (MICA) that was inserted into C2PC for intelligence operators. Prior to the creation of the Land C3I unit, was a Sr. Sw Engineer, team leader, and manager for CHI Systems from 2004 to 2008. Defined and developed new terrain analysis algorithms that were integrated into CHI's C3Core architecture (DC4S R&D predecessor) as well as fielded products such as DSTB, TAK, and DC4S. Duties included maintaining the C3Core/DC4S architecture, defining new areas for the system architecture, meeting with customers and providing solutions to their needs. Made major improvements in the C3Core/DC4S system internals, and provided software support support of CHI's network-centric C4ISR projects. Some of these major improvements include VoIP, Encryption and Authentication, Terrain Analysis Algorithms, Web Services, Unit Tracking, Embedded Device Interfaces, Networking and Communication Traffic Flow Optimization, Thread System Optimization, Greedy and Probabilistic Searches, and Software Protection algorithms for software license management. Fielded algorithms for a SIGINT program. Create VoIP, encryption, and authentication software that was validated at the US Army CECOM in 2008 by a demonstration using Windows Mobile 6 smart phones on cellular phone networks; producing high quality, low latency, encrypted voice communications.
